    <section id="id18951292">
      <title>Overview of the Character Data Type</title>
      <para id="id19911182">The <emphasis>character</emphasis> data type basically represents individual or single characters. Characters comprise a variety of symbols such as the alphabet (both upper and lower case) the numeral digits (0 to 9), punctuation, etc. All computers store character data in a one byte field as an integer value. Because a byte consists of 8 bits, this one byte field has 28 or 256 possibilities using the positive values of 0 to 255. </para>
      <para id="id23615786">Most microcomputers use the <emphasis>ASCII</emphasis> (stands for American Standard Code for Information Interchange and is pronounced "ask-key") Character Set which has established values for 0 to 127. For the values of 128 to 255 they usually use the Extended ASCII Character Set. When we hit the capital A on the keyboard, the keyboard sends a byte with the bit pattern equal to an integer 65. When the byte is sent from the memory to the monitor, the monitor converts the integer value of 65 to into the symbol of the capital A to display on the monitor. </para>
      <para id="id21758697">The character data type attributes include:</para>
      <table id="id20763270" summary="Table with data about the character data type.">
<tgroup cols="2"><colspec colnum="1" colname="c1"/>
	<colspec colnum="2" colname="c2"/>
